AGI -&nbsp; seats are open for the renewal of the South Korean Parliament >. It is a crucial event for Conservative President Yoon Suk-yeol, > that in 2022 he defeated for a handful of votes his opponent, Lee Jae-myung of the Democratic Party, but who so far had to deal with an opposition-controlled Parliament.
&nbsp;
The polls - stopped a week ago, according to the regulations in force in Seoul - give the two parties among themselves neighbors, although the popularity of Yoon is today to the minimum, strongly enshrined by the increase in food prices, by the strike of doctors in progress for weeks but also by the scandal that sees to the center his wife Kim Keon-hee, > confirmed for having accepted in gift a bag of more than 2 thousand euros>. On the other side of the barricade, however, Lee had to deal with corruption charges as well as an assault on the white weapon that in January brought him into intensive care.
&nbsp;
&nbsp; To vote - writes Asianews - are called 44,28 million voters who will go to choose the 300 new members of the National Assembly: 254 will be elected on behalf of the individual districts in which the country is divided, while another 46 seats will be assigned with the proportional system. In South Korea it is possible to take advantage of the early vote, a choice already made in recent days from more than 31% of the legal persons, including the same President Yoon. It should also be added that - while favoring the electoral system bipolarism> - there is a lot of curiosity also for the result that will get the Rebuilding Korea Party, a new party created by Cho Kuk, former Minister of Justice of the Moon administration, which according to some surveys would be credited with 20% of the consents, not so far away therefore from the People Power Party of Yoon and the Democratic Party, both accredited more than 30%.
<br The two opposing forces aspire to arrive together to overcome the threshold of the 200 seats, a possibility that would put in grave difficulty the current president. In any case, any outcome of these elections should not have great repercussions on Seoul's foreign policy, which with Yoon strengthened its links with Washington and Tokyo. The institutional structure of the country, in fact, leaves ample room for manoeuvre to the President on international policy.

